{"parse":{"title":"Mopery","pageid":1181789,"revid":857499139,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>Mopery</b> (<span class=\"nowrap\"><span class=\"IPA nopopups noexcerpt\"><a href=\"/wiki/Help:IPA/English\" title=\"Help:IPA/English\">/<span style=\"border-bottom:1px dotted\"><span title=\"/\u02c8/: primary stress follows\">\u02c8</span><span title=\"&#39;m&#39; in &#39;my&#39;\">m</span><span title=\"/o\u028a/: &#39;o&#39; in &#39;code&#39;\">o\u028a</span><span title=\"&#39;p&#39; in &#39;pie&#39;\">p</span><span title=\"/\u0259/: &#39;a&#39; in &#39;about&#39;\">\u0259</span><span title=\"&#39;r&#39; in &#39;rye&#39;\">r</span><span title=\"/i/: &#39;y&#39; in &#39;happy&#39;\">i</span></span>/</a></span></span>)<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> is a vague, informal name for minor offenses. The word is based on the verb <i>to <a href=\"https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/mope\" class=\"extiw\" title=\"wiktionary:mope\">mope</a></i>, which originally meant \u201cto wander aimlessly\u201d; it only later acquired the sense \"to be bored and depressed\". The word <i>mope</i> appears to have first been used in the 16th century, and appears in <a href=\"/wiki/Shakespeare\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Shakespeare\">Shakespeare</a>'s works. It has occasionally been put into use by police as a charge to bring when no other legitimate charge seems appropriate. It has also been used for satiric and/or comedic effect in books and films.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Definitions\">Definitions</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Mopery&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Definitions\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>In 1970, in <a href=\"/wiki/Columbus,_Ohio\" title=\"Columbus, Ohio\">Columbus, Ohio</a>, US, mopery was defined as \u201c<a href=\"/wiki/Loitering\" title=\"Loitering\">loitering</a> while walking, or walking down the street with no clear destination or purpose\u201d, and was used by police to stop and interview <a href=\"/wiki/Counterculture\" title=\"Counterculture\">counterculture</a> \"hippies\" who were regarded as unsavory.<sup class=\"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">&#91;<i><a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed\" title=\"Wikipedia:Citation needed\"><span title=\"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (August 2014)\">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup> Some of those arrested were aggressively prosecuted by public prosecutor <a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Karl_T._Chrastan&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Karl T. Chrastan (page does not exist)\">Karl T. Chrastan</a>. In discussions of law, <i>mopery</i> is used as a <a href=\"/wiki/Placeholder_name\" title=\"Placeholder name\">placeholder name</a> to mean some crime whose nature is not important to the problem at hand. This is sometimes expanded to \"mopery with intent to creep\" or \"mopery with intent to gawk\".\n</p><p>The word <i>mopery</i> has been used by authors <a href=\"/wiki/Thomas_Pynchon\" title=\"Thomas Pynchon\">Thomas Pynchon</a> <i>(<a href=\"/wiki/Gravity%27s_Rainbow\" title=\"Gravity&#39;s Rainbow\">Gravity's Rainbow</a>)</i> and <a href=\"/wiki/Dashiell_Hammett\" title=\"Dashiell Hammett\">Dashiell Hammett</a> <i>(<a href=\"/wiki/The_Thin_Man\" title=\"The Thin Man\">The Thin Man</a>)</i>, among others, for whom it is usually a comic accent. In <i><a href=\"/wiki/Catch-22\" title=\"Catch-22\">Catch-22</a></i> (<a href=\"/wiki/Joseph_Heller\" title=\"Joseph Heller\">Joseph Heller</a>, 1961), the mildly rebellious Cadet Clevinger is <a href=\"/wiki/Court-martial\" title=\"Court-martial\">court-martialed</a> by three angry officers, who accuse him of \u201cbreaking ranks while in formation, felonious assault, indiscriminate behavior, mopery, <a href=\"/wiki/High_treason\" title=\"High treason\">high treason</a>, provoking, being a <a href=\"https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/smart_aleck\" class=\"extiw\" title=\"wikt:smart aleck\">smart-guy</a>, listening to <a href=\"/wiki/Classical_music\" title=\"Classical music\">classical music</a>, and so on\u201d. Similarly, in the 1984 comedy film, <i><a href=\"/wiki/Revenge_of_the_Nerds\" title=\"Revenge of the Nerds\">Revenge of the Nerds</a></i>, mopery is defined as \"exposing oneself to a blind person.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>   According to <a href=\"/wiki/Russell_Baker\" title=\"Russell Baker\">Russell Baker</a>, \"mopery isn't a crime, but only an old policemen's joke in which it's defined as the act of displaying yourself in the nude to a blind person.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Mopery&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite id=\"CITEREFReference-OED-mopery\" class=\"citation\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://oed.com/search?searchType=dictionary&amp;q=mopery\">\"mopery\"</a>. <i><a href=\"/wiki/Oxford_English_Dictionary\" title=\"Oxford English Dictionary\">Oxford English Dictionary</a></i> (3rd ed.). Oxford University Press. September 2005.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.atitle=mopery&amp;rft.btitle=Oxford+English+Dictionary&amp;rft.edition=3rd&amp;rft.pub=Oxford+University+Press&amp;rft.date=2005-09&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Foed.com%2Fsearch%3FsearchType%3Ddictionary%26q%3Dmopery&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AMopery\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span>&#160;<span style=\"font-size:0.95em; font-size:90%; color:#555\">(Subscription or <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.oxforddnb.com/help/subscribe#public\">UK public library membership</a> required.)</span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.imdb.com/character/ch0013355/quotes\">Dudley \"Booger\" Dawson quotes</a> at the <a href=\"/wiki/Internet_Movie_Database\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Internet Movie Database\">Internet Movie Database</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a href=\"/wiki/William_Safire\" title=\"William Safire\">Safire, William</a> (June 5, 1988). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/1988/06/05/magazine/on-language-kissing-and-telling-about-kiss-and-tell.html\">\"Kissing and Telling About Kiss-and-Tell\"</a>. <i><a href=\"/wiki/On_Language\" title=\"On Language\">On Language</a></i>. The New York Times<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2014-08-17</span></span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=On+Language&amp;rft.atitle=Kissing+and+Telling+About+Kiss-and-Tell&amp;rft.date=1988-06-05&amp;rft.aulast=Safire&amp;rft.aufirst=William&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nytimes.com%2F1988%2F06%2F05%2Fmagazine%2Fon-language-kissing-and-telling-about-kiss-and-tell.html&a